General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "(p) A charter school shall provide school nutrition services in accordance with Part 2 of
2 Article 17 of this Chapter."
3 SECTION 2.(c) G.S. 115C-238.72(b) reads as rewritten:
4 "(b) Food Nutrition Service. – The local school administrative unit identified by resolution
5 shall provide, to the extent practicable, school food provide school nutrition services to the
6 regional school. school in accordance with Part 2 of Article 17 of this Chapter. For purposes of
7 federal funding through the National School Lunch Program or other federally supported food
8 nutrition service programs, the local school administrative unit identified by resolution shall be
9 permitted to include eligible students enrolled in the regional school. Other participating units
10 shall not include students enrolled in the regional school for purposes of federally supported food
11 nutrition service programs."
12 SECTION 2.(d) G.S. 116-239.8(b)(4)c. reads as rewritten:
13 "c. Food Nutrition services. – The laboratory school shall strive to ensure
14 that one hundred percent (100%) muscadine grape juice is made
15 available to students as a part of the school's nutrition program or
16 through the operation of the school's vending facilities. Laboratory
17 schools shall provide school nutrition services in accordance with Part
18 2 of Article 17 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes. Upon request,
19 the local school administrative unit in which the laboratory school is
20 located shall administer the National School Lunch Program for the
21 laboratory school in accordance with G.S. 115C-264.school."
22 SECTION 3. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
23 Public Instruction the sum of thirty-nine million dollars ($39,000,000) in recurring funds for the
24 2025-2026 fiscal year, thirty-four million dollars ($34,000,000) of which shall be allocated to
25 public school units to provide a universal breakfast program as required under G.S. 115C-263.5,
26 as enacted by this act, and five million dollars ($5,000,000) of which shall be allocated to public
27 school units to support farm-to-table initiatives pursuant to G.S. 115C-264.6, as enacted by this
28 act.
29 SECTION 4. This act becomes effective July 1, 2025, and applies beginning with
30 the 2025-2026 school year.
